  "text": "Behavioral reasons and biases can also lead to lock-in type situations in modeling. The status quo bias [CITATION_1] refers to the tendency to prefer the current solution or approach over possible new ones. The sunk cost effect [CITATION_2] refers to the phenomenon where people want to keep on committing resources to a project in which they have previously invested. This happens regardless of whether the earlier investments have been successful or not. For example, an organization can have initially adopted a certain modeling tool, such as a spreadsheet model, to support its operations. Over time this tool can have grown excessively and become unwieldy and nontransparent. Still the organization can keep on using the old model. The reason can be the sunk costs and effort put in developing the original model.",
